'''Abdul Fatawu Issahaku''' (born 8 March 2004), commonly known as '''Abdul Fatawu''', is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder#Winger|winger]] for {{English football updater|LeicestC}} club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].

== Club career ==

=== Steadfast ===
In 2019, at the age of fifteen, Fatawu started his career with [[Tamale, Ghana|Tamale]]-based club [[Steadfast FC]], in the Zone One of the [[Division One League, Ghana|Division One League]], the Ghanaian second tier. During his debut season, he immediately established himself as one of the most talented players in the league, scoring eight goals and assisting five in 13 matches before the league was halted due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Ghana|COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hafiz|first=Mohammed|date=26 March 2020|title=Meet 16 years Division One Goal Sniper Issahaku Abdul Fataw Of Steadfast FC And Former U17 Star.|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/meet-16-years-division-one-goal-sniper-issahaku-abdul-fataw-of-steadfast-fc-and-former-u17-star|url-status=live|access-date=19 March 2021|website=GhanaSoccernet|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327172519/https://ghanasoccernet.com/meet-16-years-division-one-goal-sniper-issahaku-abdul-fataw-of-steadfast-fc-and-former-u17-star |archive-date=27 March 2020 }}</ref>

In his second season, he scored 12 goals and made 12 assists in 14 league matches and picked up 8 [[man of the match]] awards.<ref>{{Cite web|date=3 August 2021|title=Rauf Salifu, Stephen Diyuo and Ernest Kusi lead nominees for the Division One League Updates-Ghana Player of the Season prize.|url=https://www.facebook.com/DivisionOneLeagueUpdateGH/photos/a.601763560205425/1416821942032912/|access-date=14 September 2021|website=Division One League Updates-Ghana}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=June 2025}} In 2021, after the [[2021 Africa U-20 Cup of Nations|Africa U-20 Cup of Nations]], Fatawu was linked with several European teams, some of them being [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], and [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Osei |first=Bernard Esar Ebo |date=7 April 2022 |title=#Donkomi: Abdul Fatawu Issahaku signs five-year deal with Sporting Club |url=https://citisportsonline.com/2022/04/06/donkomi-abdul-fatawu-issahaku-signs-five-year-deal-with-sporting-club/ |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=Citi Sports Online }}</ref><ref name=":4">{{Cite web |last=Dawes |first=Olly |date=7 April 2022 |title=Wonderkid Abdul Fatawu Issahku won't be signing for Liverpool after all |url=https://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2022/04/07/liverpool-sporting-abdul-fatal-issahaku/ |access-date=10 April 2022 |website=HITC }}</ref> In October 2021, Fatawu joined [[Dreams F.C. (Ghana)|Dreams]] on a loan until 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|date=14 October 2021|title=Ghanaian youngster Abdul Fatawu Issahaku joins Dreams FC on loan- Reports|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghanaian-youngster-abdul-fatawu-issahaku-joins-dreams-fc-on-loan-reports|access-date=4 January 2022|website=GhanaSoccernet|language=en}}</ref> In the same month, he was included in [[The Guardian]]'s "Next Generation 2021", and was described by them as "arguably the best African prospect of his generation".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2021/oct/07/next-generation-2021-60-of-the-best-young-talents-in-world-football|title=Next Generation 2021 by The Guardian|website=[[The Guardian]] |date=7 October 2021 |access-date=27 March 2022|language=en |last1=Christenson |first1=Marcus }}</ref>

=== Sporting CP ===
In April 2022, he was signed by [[Sporting CP]] on a five-year contract with a release clause of €60&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |date=7 April 2022 |title=Sporting Lisbon sign Ghana teenager Issahaku |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61023569 |access-date=8 April 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=6 April 2022 |title=Abdul Fatawu Issahaku é Leão |url=https://www.sporting.pt/pt/noticias/futebol/2022-04-06/abdul-fatawu-issahaku-e-leao |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=sporting.pt |language=pt-pt}}</ref> This brought finality to rumours of him joining Sporting CP on loan from Liverpool and other transfer saga rumour.<ref name=":4" /> Prior to signing officially Fatawu had been at the club since February and had been training with the U-23 side. As he was an under age player at the time, and with the season already ongoing, he couldn't be registered with the first-team until the 2022–23 season, then, he began to train with the [[Sporting CP Youth Academy|B team]] until available to play for the professional team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/sporting/detalhe/prodigio-ganes-contratado-pelo-sporting-ja-trabalha-na-academia|title=Prodígio ganês contratado pelo Sporting já trabalha na Academia|language=pt|access-date=27 March 2022|archive-date=27 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220327080415/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/sporting/detalhe/prodigio-ganes-contratado-pelo-sporting-ja-trabalha-na-academia|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/sporting/detalhe/issahaku-atinge-maioridade|title=Issahaku atinge maioridade|access-date=27 March 2022|language=pt|archive-date=27 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220327080413/https://www.record.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-bwin/sporting/detalhe/issahaku-atinge-maioridade|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Ahead of the 2022–23 season, Fatawu was named in the squad for pre-season training and tour for the first team.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 May 2022 |title='Outstanding talent' Abdul Fatawu Issahaku included in Sporting CP's plans for pre-season |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/outstanding-talent-abdul-fatawu-issahaku-included-in-sporting-cps-plans-for-pre-season |access-date=14 August 2022 |website=GhanaSoccernet |language=en}}</ref> He was involved in the team's preparations prior to the start of the season playing his first pre-season game against Belgium side [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Royale Union]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 July 2022 |title=Sporting CP deploy Fatawu Issahaku in an unfamiliar role during pre-season friendly - MyJoyOnline.com |url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/sporting-cp-deploy-fatawu-issahaku-in-an-unfamiliar-role-during-pre-season-friendly/ |access-date=14 August 2022 |website=myjoyonline.com |language=en-US}}</ref> On 7 August 2022, he was named on the bench for the first match of the season. The following weekend he made his debut after coming on in the 80th minute for [[Francisco Trincão]] in Sporting CP's 3–0 victory over [[Rio Ave F.C.|Rio Ave]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 August 2022 |title=Sporting CP win first home game of 2022/2023 |url=https://www.sporting.pt/en/news/football/main-team/2022-08-14/sporting-cp-win-first-home-game-of-2022/2023 |access-date=14 August 2022 |website=sporting.pt |language=en}}</ref>

====Loan to Leicester City====
On 31 August 2023, Fatawu signed for [[EFL Championship]] side [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on a season-long loan from Sporting CP.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abdul Fatawu Makes Leicester City Switch |url=https://www.lcfc.com/news/3661040/abdul-fatawu-makes-leicester-city-switch |publisher=Leicester City F.C. |date=31 August 2023}}</ref> He made his club debut in the EFL Championship three days later, coming on as a 54th-minute substitute in a 1–0 home loss to [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leicester City 0–1 Hull City: Liam Delap strikes to end Foxes' perfect start to new season|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66624455|website=BBC Sport |date=2 September 2023|access-date=3 January 2024}}</ref> On 21 October, he scored his first goal for the club in a 3–1 away win against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Swansea City 1–3 Leicester City: Leaders come from behind to set second-tier record|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67108814|website=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2023|access-date=3 January 2024}}</ref> On 23 April 2024, he scored his first professional hat-trick, in a 5–0 home win against promotion rivals, [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leicester on brink of promotion after thumping Saints|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cv2dqg456n8t?page=2|website=BBC Sport |date=23 April 2024|access-date=24 April 2024}}</ref> There was a clause inserted into the loan that required Leicester to purchase Fatawu upon promotion for €17&nbsp;million, which they did in May 2024. 50% of the difference between the sale price to Sporting (€1.2&nbsp;million) and Leicester was provided to Fatawu's original club, Steadfast FC, who had inserted a sell-on clause in his sale to Sporting.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kinyanjui |first=Mark |date=7 May 2024 |title=The tantalising millions Ghananian side Steadfast FC will earn from Abdul Fatawu's permanent Leicester City move |url=https://www.pulsesports.co.ke/football/story/the-tantalising-millions-ghananian-side-steadfast-fc-will-earn-from-abdul-fatawus-permanent-leicester-city-move-2024050708581962707 |access-date=2025-01-06 |website=Pulse Sports Kenya |language=en}}</ref>

=== Leicester City ===
[[File:Leicester City Players 23082025 (8).jpg|thumb|Abdul Fatawu warming up before the second-half starts in [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]’s match against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]].]]

On 1 July 2024, Leicester City activated the buy clause and signed for €10&nbsp;million on a permanent five-year deal contract with €7&nbsp;million additional fee.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Millar |first=Colin |title=Leicester sign Fatawu after triggering buy option |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5617984/2024/07/16/abdul-fatawu-leicester-transfer-news/ |access-date=2024-08-21 |work=The New York Times |date=17 July 2024 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As a result, his jersey number changed from No. 18 to No. 7.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Spinney |first=Fraser |date=15 August 2024 |title=Leicester City confirm iconic shirt number changes for Wilfred Ndidi and Abdul Fatawu |url=https://www.leicestercity.news/news/leicester-city-confirm-iconic-shirt-number-changes-for-wilfred-ndidi-and-abdul-fatawu/ |access-date=2024-08-21 |website=Leicester City News |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 19 August 2024, he made his first Premier League debut as part of the first team squad for Leicester City against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]. In that same game, Fatawu provided his first Premier League assist for [[Jamie Vardy]] in a 1–1 home draw.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ayamga |first=Emmanuel |date=20 August 2024 |title=Fatawu Issahaku's brilliant assist helps Leicester City secure draw vs Tottenham |url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/sports/football/fatawu-issahakus-brilliant-assist-helps-leicester-city-secure-draw-vs-tottenham/e9qst54 |access-date=2024-08-21 |website=Pulse Ghana |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Davies |first=Luke |date=20 August 2024 |title=Abdul Fatawu explains what Steve Cooper did to inspire Leicester City fightback |url=https://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/abdul-fatawu-reveals-what-steve-9496717 |access-date=2024-08-21 |website=Leicestershire Live |language=en}}</ref> On 13 December 2025, he scored from his own half in a 3–1 victory over [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/leicester-city-boss-praises-fatawu-issahaku-for-extraordinary-goal-in-ipswich-win |title=Leicester City boss praises Fatawu Issahaku for extraordinary goal in Ipswich win |publisher=GhanaSoccernet |date=13 December 2025 }}</ref>

== International career ==

=== Youth team ===
In 2018, Fatawu was part of Ghana's [[Ghana national under-17 football team|national under-17 team]] managed by [[Abdul-Karim Zito|Karim Zito]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darkwah |first=Frank |date=20 August 2018 |title=Black Starlets Coach name squad for WAFU U17 Championship |url=https://ghanasportsonline.com/2018/08/black-starlets-coach-name-squad-for-wafu-u17-championship/ |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=Ghana Sports Online }}</ref> The team reached the finals of the 2018 WAFU Zone B U-17 Cup of Nations. They however lost in the final to rivals Nigeria via a 3–1 penalty shootout after a 1–1 draw after regulation time, with Fatawu missing his penalty in the shootout.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Quao |first=Nathan |date=16 September 2018 |title=WAFU Zone B U17: Ghana loses final to Nigeria on penalties |url=https://citinewsroom.com/2018/09/wafu-zone-b-u17-ghana-loses-final-to-nigeria-on-penalties/ |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=CitiNewsroom }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Abayomi |first=Tosin |date=15 September 2018 |title=Golden Eaglets beat Ghana 3–1 on penalties in final |url=https://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/2019-u-17-afcon-qualifier-golden-eaglets-beat-ghana-3-1-on-penalties-in-final/04yz396 |access-date=10 April 2022 |newspaper=[[Pulse Nigeria]]}}</ref> Fatawu remained a member of the Ghana U-17 team and served as captain of the team in 2020, playing during the [[2021 Africa U-17 Cup of Nations qualification|2021 Africa U-17 Cup of Nations qualifiers]], during 2020 WAFU Zone B U-17 Cup of Nations.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 January 2021 |title=WAFU U-17 Cup of Nations: Ben names Ghana squad to face Nigeria |url=https://www.ghanafa.org/wafu-u-17-cup-of-nations-ben-names-ghana-squad-to-face-nigeria |access-date=8 April 2022 |website=Ghana Football Association }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kwafo |first=Eric Nana Yaw |date=6 January 2021 |title=Ghana U-17 coach Ben Fokuo names 28-man squad for WAFU Zone B tournament |url=https://www.modernghana.com/sports/1053753/ghana-u-17-coach-ben-fokuo-names28-man-squad.html |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=Modern Ghana }}</ref> At the tournament he scored the equalising penalty in Ghana's 1–1 draw against [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kwafo |first=Eric Nana Yaw |date=9 January 2021 |title=WAFU Zone B U-17 tournament: Issahaku scores for Ghana in draw against Nigeria |url=https://www.modernghana.com/sports/1054374/wafu-zone-b-u-17-tournament-issahaku-scores-for.html |access-date=10 April 2022 |website=Modern Ghana }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Tournoi UFOA B U17 : le Ghana et le Nigeria s'accrochent 1–1 |url=http://fr.cafonline.com/news-center/news/tournoi-ufoa-b-u17-le-ghana-et-le-nigeria-s-accrochent-1-1 |access-date=8 April 2022 |website=CAFOnline |publisher=CAF-Confedération Africaine du Football |language=fr}}</ref> Ghana were eliminated from the competition after losing 3–1 against [[Ivory Coast national under-17 football team|Ivory Coast]] in their final group game. Ghana's only goal of the game was assisted by Fatawu.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ghana crash out of WAFU Zone B tournament after 3–1 loss to Cote D'Ivoire |url=https://www.ghanafa.org/ghana-crashes-out-of-wafu-u-17-zone-b-tournament-after-excruciating-loss-to-cote-divoire |access-date=16 April 2022 |website=Ghana Football Association }}</ref>

The following year, due to his impressive form, Fatawu was promoted into the [[Ghana national under-20 football team|under-20 squad]] at the age of 16, despite being much younger than the majority of his teammates. He was later selected to take part in the [[2021 Africa U-20 Cup of Nations]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|last=Football|first=CAF-Confedération Africaine du|title=Abdul Fatawu Issahaku – We're here to bring back the love|url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/abdul-fatawu-issahaku-we-re-here-to-bring-back-the-love|access-date=19 March 2021|website=CAFOnline.com|language=en}}</ref> During the competition, he played all of the ''Black Satellites''<nowiki/>' matches, scoring two goals in the group stages to help his side win the title for the fourth time in its history.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=6 March 2021 |title=Ghana beat debutants Uganda to clinch Total AFCON U20 title |url=https://www.cafonline.com/total-u20-africa-cup-of-nations/2021/news/ghana-beat-debutants-uganda-to-clinch-total-afcon-u20-title |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129023209/https://www.cafonline.com/total-u20-africa-cup-of-nations/2021/news/ghana-beat-debutants-uganda-to-clinch-total-afcon-u20-title |archive-date=29 January 2023 |access-date=19 March 2021 |website=CAFOnline.com |publisher=Confedération Africaine du Football (CAF) |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=11 March 2021|title=U-20 AFCON: Abdul Fatawu Issahaku presents trophy to 'father' Haruna Iddrisu|url=https://citisportsonline.com/2021/03/11/u-20-afcon-abdul-fatawu-issahaku-presents-trophy-to-father-haruna-iddrisu/|access-date=19 March 2021|website=Citi Sports Online|language=en-US}}</ref> In that occasion, he was also adjudged as the Best Player of the Tournament.<ref>{{Cite news|title=U-20 Afcon: Issahaku Abdul Fatawu named Most Valuable Player of the tournament|url=https://www.modernghana.com/sports/1066202/u-20-afcon-issahaku-abdul-fatawu-named-most-valua.html|access-date=19 March 2021|website=Modern Ghana|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":03">{{cite web |date=7 March 2021 |title=Ghana's Fatawu named Total U20 AFCON player of the tournament |url=https://www.cafonline.com/total-u20-africa-cup-of-nations/2021/news/ghana-s-fatawu-named-total-u20-afcon-player-of-the-tournament |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230225015700/https://www.cafonline.com/total-u20-africa-cup-of-nations/2021/news/ghana-s-fatawu-named-total-u20-afcon-player-of-the-tournament |archive-date=25 February 2023 |publisher=Confédération Africaine de Football}}</ref>

=== Senior team ===
In March 2021, after his exploits with the U-20 side, Fatawu was given his first call-up to the [[Ghana national football team|senior team]] by [[Charles Akonnor|C.K. Akonnor]], as the ''Black Stars'' challenged [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] and [[São Tomé and Príncipe national football team|São Tomé and Príncipe]] in two [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations qualification Group C|qualifying matches]] for the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=18 March 2021|title=Ghana youth star Abdul Fatawu Issahaku opens up on receiving first Black Stars call up|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-youth-star-abdul-fatawu-issahaku-opens-up-on-receiving-first-black-stars-call-up|access-date=19 March 2021|website=GhanaSoccernet|language=en}}</ref> He was called up alongside teammates from the U-20 AFCON winning team, [[Philomon Baffour]] and [[Ibrahim Danlad]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Teye |first=Prince Narkortu |date=16 March 2021 |title=Ghana call up 17-year-old U20 Afcon star Issahaku and two others for South Africa qualifier |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-call-up-17-year-old-u20-afcon-star-issahaku-and-two-others-/rkmxc5dbyqur122wkqrh361md |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref>

Fatawu scored a free-kick goal against Uzbekistan when the Black Stars' B Team played [[Uzbekistan national football team|Uzbekistan]] at the [[Markaziy Stadium]]. Even though the game ended 2–1 for Uzbekistan,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Uzbekistan 2–1 Ghana B: Issahaku's super strike not enough for Black Stars|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/uzbekistan-2-1-ghana-b-issahakus-super-strike-not-enough-for/19f5t08sugugy181tg07z5r9hh|url-status=live|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Goal (website)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210326194959/https://www.goal.com/en/news/uzbekistan-2-1-ghana-b-issahakus-super-strike-not-enough-for/19f5t08sugugy181tg07z5r9hh |archive-date=26 March 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Black Stars B suffer 2–1 to defeat to Uzbekistan in friendly|url=https://www.modernghana.com/sports/1070728/black-stars-b-suffer-2-1-to-defeat-to-uzbekistan.html|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Modern Ghana|language=en}}</ref> he was highly praised by his performance.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Issahaku: Tanko wants Ghana opportunities for Salzburg-linked teenage prodigy|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/issahaku-tanko-wants-ghana-opportunities-for-salzburg-linked/1rp4az28qryfy1ig2yqcs4lr3w|url-status=live|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Goal (website)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210407155724/https://www.goal.com/en/news/issahaku-tanko-wants-ghana-opportunities-for-salzburg-linked/1rp4az28qryfy1ig2yqcs4lr3w |archive-date=7 April 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ghana starlets Issahaku and co. warned against complacency|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-starlets-issahaku-and-co-warned-against-complacency/1u0g6rd61x8y01u8083s7q7tmw|url-status=live|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Goal (website)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210323183836/https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-starlets-issahaku-and-co-warned-against-complacency/1u0g6rd61x8y01u8083s7q7tmw |archive-date=23 March 2021 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Ghana starlet Abdul Fatawu Issahaku weighing up Qatar, Switzerland and Italy offers|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-starlet-abdul-fatawu-issahakuweighing-up-qatar-switzerland-/iv3ey2mxcej61nonnrrz5gja8|url-status=live|access-date=9 April 2021|website=Goal (website)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210331163801/https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-starlet-abdul-fatawu-issahakuweighing-up-qatar-switzerland-/iv3ey2mxcej61nonnrrz5gja8 |archive-date=31 March 2021 }}</ref>

In September 2021, Fatawu made his debut for the Black Stars in a 3–1 victory over [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]] in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round#Group G|2022 FIFA World Cup qualifier]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=9 October 2021|title=Teenager Fatawu Issahaku impresses on Black Stars debut|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/teenager-fatawu-issahaku-impresses-on-black-stars-debut|access-date=10 October 2021|website=GhanaSoccernet|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=9 October 2021|title=Abdul Fatawu Issahaku starts against Zimbabwe|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/abdul-fatawu-issahaku-starts-against-zimbabwe|url-status=live|access-date=10 October 2021|website=ghanafa.org|publisher=Ghana Football Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211010043707/https://www.ghanafa.org/abdul-fatawu-issahaku-starts-against-zimbabwe |archive-date=10 October 2021 }}</ref> Fatawu made the 28-man [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations squads#Ghana|squad]] for [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |date=3 January 2022 |title=Milovan Rajevac names squad for Total Energies 2021 AFCON |url=https://www.ghanafa.org/coach-milovan-rajevac-names-squad-for-total-energies-2021-afcon |access-date=9 April 2022 |publisher=[[Ghana Football Association]]}}</ref> He was the youngest player in the Ghanaian team and the fourth youngest at the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 January 2022 |title=The six youngest players at the 2021 Africa Cup of Nations |url=https://www.michezoafrika.com/news/the-six-youngest-players-at-the-2021-africa-cup-of-nations-/27482 |access-date=9 April 2022 |website=Michezo Afrika |language=en}}</ref> On 27 September 2021, Fatawu scored his debut goal for the Ghana senior team against [[Nicaragua national football team|Nicaragua]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 September 2022 |title=Fatawu Issahaku scores debut goal as Black Stars record narrow win over Nicaragua - MyJoyOnline.com |url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/fatawu-issahaku-scores-debut-goal-as-black-stars-record-narrow-win-over-nicaragua/ |access-date=2 November 2022 |website=myjoyonline.com |language=en-US}}</ref>

